SIMPLE: pyrometer
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pyrometer
<hw>Py*rom"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Pyro-</ets>
+ <ets>-meter</ets>: cf. F. <ets>pyrom⟦egrave⟧tre</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument used for measuring
the expansion of solid bodies by heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument for measuring
degrees of heat above those indicated by the mercurial
thermometer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It is usually constructed so as to register the change
which the heat to be measured produces in the length of some expansible
substance, as a metallic rod, or in the intensity of a thermo-electric
current.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyrometrical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Pyrometric</ent>⟦br⟧
